our inner child is independent of us.

I agree with all of the psychologists mentioned.  I agree that wounds from our childhood can cause present and future problems. I agree that we need to remedy them through therapy. I do not agree with referring to ourselves in 3rd person or speaking as if

You don’t have a split psyche. There aren’t two forms of you- one being damaged and one being whole. There isn’t an inner child residing in you. It’s YOU. All of that is YOU. The concept of having an “inner child” is pseudoscience.

My issue with the term “inner child” isn’t necessarily with its origin. It’s that in 2022 we are now referring to ourselves in 3rd person when speaking of our trauma in the present. This, to me, resembles dissociative behaviors, and I don’t necessarily think it’s productive.
In 1991 an art therapist wrote a book entitled Recovery of Your Inner Child. The book detailed how to “re-parent” your inner child through art therapy and journaling.
I wanna finish that thread but Twitter is down!!

Finally the term “inner child” was fully developed by psychologist Arthur Janov who created “primal therapy”. He believed that neurosis was caused by repressed pain from childhood trauma. The way to fix the issue is by recalling the trauma and expressing the feelings in therapy.

In 1923 this term was utilized by Emmet Fox a “spiritual” leader that wrote the book The Wonder Child which included biblical passages to instruct people to “unlock” their true selves and obtain “mystic power”.
Here are his 12 archetypes. The Innocent is also identified as The Child. https://t.co/wqxWkVVHuv

“Inner child” was initially derived from psychologist Carl Jung’s Jungian archetype. Jung was a follower of Freud and was fascinated about the “unconscious mind”. His archetype was based on the idea that our past directs/influences our present behavior.
I hate when people use the term “inner child”. Your inner child is YOU….in the present! It’s not your inner child that’s hurt; it’s YOU. Why do we have to refer to ourselves in 3rd person?
